T3  - ACC 22. Washington, DC United States.
A1  - Pan J.A.
A1  - Siggins C.
A1  - Loffler A.
A1  - Kuruvilla S.
A1  - Epstein F.
A1  - Kramer C.M.
A1  - Keeley E.
A1  - Gan L.-M.
A1  - Salerno M. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Background: Heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF) is a heterogenous disease syndrome associated with metabolic disorders. The purpose of this HFpEF study is to estimate correlations between cardiometabolic plasma biomarkers and cardiac magnetic resonance (CMR). Method(s): We enrolled 18 patients with HFpEF and 15 healthy controls. They underwent CMR at 1.5T with quantitative first-pass perfusion imaging and T1 mapping. Extracellular volume (ECV) and myocardial perfusion reserve (MPR) were measured. Plasma samples were analyzed with the Olink Cardiometabolic 92 biomarker assay. Correlation coefficients with 95% confidence intervals for MPR and ECV were calculated with the 92 plasma biomarkers via orthogonal projection to latent structures by partial least squares analysis. Result(s): Total of 12 biomarkers had significant correlation coefficients (Figure 1). Five correlated with MPR (blue circles), six correlated with ECV (yellow circles), and one correlated with both (green box). All others were not significant (grey circles). NCAM1, PCOLCE, and CHL1 had high absolute MPR correlation coefficients of 0.27 [0.12, 0.35], -0.19 [-0.38, -0.03], and 0.30 [0.18, 0.39] respectively. They are associated with endothelial dysfunction in atherosclerosis, cardiac fibrosis, and insulin production respectively. Conclusion(s): ECV and MPR correlate differentially in plasma biomarker patterns. Top predictors of MPR consisted of biomarkers of metabolic syndromes and cardiac remodeling. [Formula presented]Copyright © 2022 American College of Cardiology Foundation
