79. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2015982286
T1  - STUDY OF SOME HORMONAL PARAMETERS ASSOCIATED WITH POLYCYSTIC OVARY SYNDROME (PCOS) IN TYPE2 DIABETIC WOMEN (T2DM)
A1  - Al_Husaini F.K.A.
A1  - Khalifa A.A. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is the most common endocrine and metabolic disorders in premenopausal women which is characterized by hyperandrogenemia and hyperinsulinemia that lead to infertility due to non-ovulation. The current study aimed to evaluate some hormonal and biochemical parameters associated with polycystic ovary syndrome in diabetic women type 2. The current study included one hundred twenty premenopausal women with age ranged (35-45) years divided into four groups and each group have 30 women at the following: group (1) control group, group (2) women with PCOS, group (3): women with T2DM and group (4): women with PCOS and T2DM. The results of luteinizing hormone (LH), luteinizing hormone/ follicle stimulating hormone (LH /FSH) ratio, prolactin (PRL), testosterone and dihydrotestosterone (DHT) revealed that the second and fourth groups were increased significantly (p < 0.05) compared with the first group. While, the result of FSH in the second and fourth groups decreased significantly (p < 0.05) compared with the first group. No significant differences in FSH, LH, LH/FSH ratio and prolactin in third group compared with the first group. While, testosterone and DHT in third group was increased significant (p < 0.05) compared with first group. The physiological impact of PCOS and T2DM to our parameters are discussed due to effect of the PCOS and T2DM on the hyperandrogenimia (high levels of androgen hormones) and hyperinsulinemia (high insulin level) and their effects.Copyright © 2021. All Rights Reserved.
