101. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2011065381
T1  - Role of central venous-arterial PCO2 difference in prediction of clinical outcome in ICU septic patients
A1  - Abdalazeem E.S.
A1  - Abdelgawad B.
A1  - El-Rahman A.H.A. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Background: Identification of tissue hypoxia and hypoperfusion plays an important role in the management of critically ill patients. Although the venous-arterial PCO2 difference (DELTAPCO2) cannot serve as a marker of tissue hypoxia, it is considered a marker of the adequacy of venous blood flow (Cardiac output). The present study aimed to evaluate the role of venous-arterial PCO2 gradient in prediction of outcome in septic patients admitted to ICU. Patients and Methods: 100 adult patients fulfilled the criteria of severe sepsis or septic shock admitted to Emergency Intensive Care Unit, were divided in two groups according to DELTAPCO2. The high DELTApCO2 group (DELTApCO2 > 6 mmHg) included 58 patients and the normal DELTApCO2 (DELTApCO2 <= 6 mmHg) included 42 patients. Clinical scoring systems were recorded. Clinical outcome including organ dysfunction and mortality was recorded. Result(s): The high DELTAPCO2 group showed significant lower blood glucose level (p = 0.038) than the normal DELTAPCO2 group. Serum lactate, heart rate, and APACHE score were significantly higher in high DELTAPCO2 group than normal DELTAPCO2 group (p, 0.012, 0.013, and 0.020, respectively). As regard to the clinical outcome, patient mortality was significantly higher (p = 0.042) in high DELTAPCO2 group than normal DELTAPCO2 group and the number of organ dysfunction was higher in high DELTAPCO2 group than normal DELTAPCO2 group but not reached a significant level (p = 0.625). Conclusion(s): DELTAPCO2 is a reliable index for early prediction of clinical outcome including organ dysfunction and mortality in patients with sepsis and septic shock.Copyright © 2021 The Author(s). Published by Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.
