106. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2008412515
ID  - 33130244 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=33130244]
T1  - Endovascular embolization of wide-necked bifurcation aneurysms with the use of pCONus device: A systematic review and meta-analysis
A1  - Krupa K.
A1  - Brzegowy P.
A1  - Kucybala I.
A1  - Lasocha B.
A1  - Urbanik A.
A1  - Popiela T.J. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Background: The following study aimed to summarize the overall safety and efficacy of the pCONus device in the treatment of wide-necked bifurcation aneurysms. Material(s) and Method(s): Major electronic medical databases were thoroughly searched to identify relevant studies. Data regarding the type of included studies, type of aneurysm and its location, treatment results measured in Raymond-Roy Occlusion Class (RROC) and its complications, as well as patients' neurological outcome at the discharge were extracted from the eligible studies and included in the meta-analysis. The subgroup analyses dependent on the aneurysm rupture status were also conducted. Result(s): A total of 8 studies (198 patients with 200 aneurysms) were included in this meta-analysis. The most common localization of the treated aneurysms was the middle cerebral artery with its pooled prevalence estimate (PPE) of 44.5%. Immediately after the procedure, RROC I (complete obliteration of the aneurysm) was observed in 46.8%, RROC II in 32.9%, while RROC III (residual aneurysm) in 20.3% of the patients. In a short-term follow-up, PPE of RROC I was 55.0%, RROC II 29.0%, and RROC III 16.1%. The PPE of intraprocedural complications was 17.3%, the most frequent were thromboembolic events, which were observed in 12.1% of all procedures. Poor neurological outcome at the discharge was noted with PPE of 9.6%. Conclusion(s): The effectiveness and safety of wide-necked bifurcation aneurysm treatment utilizing the pCONus device is moderate. There is still a need for a consensus regarding the effective antiplatelet regimen in furtherance of diminishing the rate of thromboembolic events.Copyright © 2020 Elsevier Inc.
