107. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 638193921
T1  - Major bleeding and thromboembolic events in venovenous ECMO-patients with isolated respiratory failure. A retrospective analysis
T3  - International Congress of the European Respiratory Society, ERS 2021. Virtual.
A1  - Baumgartner S.
A1  - Lubnow M.
A1  - Malfertheiner M.
A1  - Philipp A.
A1  - Foltan M.
A1  - Lunz D.
A1  - Muller T.
A1  - Fisser C. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Background: Bleeding or thrombotic events are common during veno-venous extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (vvECMO). It is unknown if these associations are driven by the ECMO system or by multi-organ failure. The aim of the study was to assess bleeding and thromboembolic rates in patients without other organ failure than respiratory. Method(s): Patients requiring vvECMO from March 2009 to October 2017 were retrospectively included. Exclusion criteria was organ failure other than respiratory. Major bleeding was defined as a decrease in haemoglobin level >=2g/dl or requirement of >=2 packed red cells/24 hours, retroperitoneal, pulmonary or central nervous system bleeding or bleeding requiring surgical intervention. Thromboembolic events were assessed by duplex sonography and/or by CT-scan. Parameters of coagulation were evaluated on a daily basis. Result(s): Of 601 patients, 123 patients were eligible for the analysis. Patients were 49 years old with a median SOFA score of 8 [7-9]. Major bleeding was observed in 73% with 35% on the day or the day after ECMO initiation. Decrease of pCO2 after ECMO initiation was more pronounced in patients with intracranial bleeding compared to those without. Thromboembolic events were noted in 28%. Level of aPTT, fibrinogen, platelet count or D-dimers neither affected bleeding nor thromboembolic rate. Conclusion(s): Bleeding and thromboembolic complications appeared in 73% and 28% in patients requiring vvECMO without other organ failure than respiratory. Decline of pCO2 after ECMO initiation was higher in those suffering from intracranial bleeding. Chemistries were neither associated with bleeding nor with thromboembolic events.
