120. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2011746432
T1  - ACUTE MULTIFOCAL ISCHEMIC STROKE AND ACUTE LIMB ISCHEMIA IN A PATIENT WITH COVD-19 INFECTION
T3  - ACC.21. Virtual, Online.
A1  - Khan A.
A1  - Bangash S.
A1  - Heath T. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Background SARS-CoV-2 infection induces hypercoagulability leading to the development of arterial and venous thrombosis; the underlying mechanism of which is still unclear. Case A 63-year-old Hispanic man presented due to shortness of breath, and fatigue for the past four days. He had a respiratory rate of 25 with SpO2 of 80% on room air, improving to 91% on a 15L NRB mask. Laboratory data included WBC count 13.4, d-dimer 585, CRP >30. ABG: pH 7.45, PCO2 31, P02 71, HCO3 21.3, FiO2 100%, and P/F 71. CXR showed bilateral interstitial infiltrates, and the SARS-CoV2 PCR test was positive. The patient was admitted with severe ARDS due to COVID-19 infection. Medications included Dexamethasone, full dose Lovenox; convalescent plasma also received. However, he continued deteriorating, requiring intubation and mechanical ventilation. The post-intubation course was complicated by a right-sided pneumothorax, and the pallor of the left lower limb, which was cold to touch with absent distal pulses, necessitating initiation of heparin drip. WBC count worsened to 27.2, and d-dimer levels to 102,204. Moreover, a left-sided weakness was noted on sedation holiday. Decision-making Arterial Doppler ultrasound confirmed absent flow in the infrapopliteal vessels. CT brain showed potentially acute multifocal bilateral cerebral, left parieto-occipital, and left frontal region infarcts with dilated ventricles, and inferior effacement of the fourth ventricle. Vascular, neurosurgery and palliative teams were involved; the patient&apos;s family decided to withdraw care. The uniqueness of this case is due to the catastrophic manifestations of hypercoagulability associated with COVID-19 infection. Conclusion The underlying mechanisms for a hypercoagulable state in COVID-19 are yet to be elucidated. Thus far, we have found a case series of three patients with bilateral infarcts with COVID-19, and a case report on massive bilateral stroke in a COVID-19 patient. However, we were unable to find any cases reporting concurrent development of bilateral stroke and acute limb ischemia. Therefore, this case contributes further to the limited literature on the systemic thromboembolic complications associated with COVID-19.Copyright © 2021 American College of Cardiology Foundation
