156. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634009984
T1  - Completeness of the circle of Willis and its relationship with secondary collaterals in acute ischemic stroke patients
T3  - 12th World Stroke Congress 2020. Vienna Austria.
A1  - Konduri P.
A1  - Zeeuw A.
A1  - Boodt N.
A1  - Jansen I.
A1  - Lingsma H.
A1  - Dippel D.
A1  - Coutinho J.
A1  - Sprengers M.
A1  - Van Es A.
A1  - Yo L.
A1  - Van Den Wijngaard I.
A1  - Van Zwam W.
A1  - Emmer B.
A1  - Van Den Berg R.
A1  - Yoo A.
A1  - Van Doormaal P.J.
A1  - Lycklama G.
A1  - Nijeholt A.
A1  - Van Der Lugt A.
A1  - Boiten J.
A1  - Marquering H.
A1  - Majoie C. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Background and Aims: We hypothesize that the primary collateral circulation through the circle of Willis (CoW) and the secondary (leptomeningeal) collateral circulation are recruited with a similar underlying mechanism. In this study, we assess the completeness of CoW (cCoW) and its relationship with the collateral score (CS), also after accounting for the occlusion location. Method(s): We analyzed patients from the MRCLEAN Registry who were enrolled between March 2014 and October 2015. We assessed the anterior and posterior cerebral arteries along with anterior and posterior communicating arteries mainly on thin slice, good quality, baseline CT Angiography images. Absence, hypoplasia (except AComA), or presence of CoW arteries were awarded 0, 1 or 2 points respectively, resulting in a maximum of 14 points. We used Kruskal-Wallis (KW) test to compare the cCoW for different grades of CS. We similarly assessed this relationship separately for proximal (ICA,ICA-T) and distal (M1, M2) occlusions. Result(s): Two-hundred-sixty-nine patients were included and the median cCoW was 10(IQR:10-12). 25 (9.3%) patients had a complete CoW, 17(6.3%) had only one hypoplastic artery. Most frequently absent or hypoplastic artery segments were left PComA (155(57.6%)) and left P1 (34(12.6%)). Higher cCoW was observed in higher CS grades (cCOW 10(IQR: 9-10) for CS=0 and cCoW 11(IQR:10-12) for CS=3; p=0.03). Similar trend was also observed for proximal occlusions (p=0.04), but not for distal occlusions. Conclusion(s): Due to the small differences in cCOW for CS grades, we cannot conclude that the primary and secondary collaterals are recruited similarly.
