157. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634005110
T1  - Ct perfusion study in predicting irreversible coma
T3  - 12th World Stroke Congress 2020. Vienna Austria.
A1  - Murti S.
A1  - Lee G.
A1  - Ahmed I. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Background And Aims: An American Academy of Neurology policy statement declared that while computed tomography, magnetic resonance imaging, electroencephalogram, apnea tests, and evoked potentials were helpful in confirming coma irreversibility, none were completely diagnostic.We present a case in which a patient becomes comatose after a massive subarachnoid hemorrhage from an intracranial aneurysm. We established coma irreversibility through the use of a CT perfusion study. We posit that a CT perfusion study, a common component of neurological exams, can demonstrate coma irreversibility and is a vital addition to evaluations of comatose patients. Method(s): A 47-year-old female with a history of headaches, hypertension, and cocaine abuse was admitted with severe mental changes. Head CT showed diffuse subarachnoid bleed and hydrocephalus. Her blood pressure was elevated and despite medical intervention she became comatose. She underwent ventriculostomy. Result(s): Neurologically the patient remained comatose, on the ventilator with facet quadriplegia, no spontaneous movements, and absent oculo responses on cold caloric testing. Corneal reflexes, deep tendon reflexes, and response to sensory stimulation were absent. CT perfusion showed a marked decrease in whole brain perfusion, increased transit time, with no flow. The mean transit time was 10- 15, and time to peak was absent bilaterally. The patient's repeat EEG was consistent with electrocerebral silence. Somatosensory evoked responses showed absent cortical responses and the patient had absolute apnea with Pco2 from 35 to 71. The patient was subsequently withdrawn from care. Conclusion(s): In this case, CT perfusion scan showed clear evidence of coma irreversibility, and demonstrates how this should be included in comatose exams.
