161. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2008382008
T1  - Replication in Evidence-Based Aphasia Treatments
T3  - American Congress of Rehabilitation Medicine 2020. Atlanta United States.
A1  - Karidas S.
A1  - Hinckley J. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Research Objectives: The purpose of this review is to discuss important considerations in the replication of existing research on evidence-based aphasia treatments. The audience will be able to differentiate and define different replication types, value the importance of replication research, and apply their new knowledge to their own research. Design(s): Studies were identified through a systematic review of all literature listed on the ASHA Practice Portal in September 2018. Setting(s): Aphasia treatments listed in the ASHA Practice Portal were analyzed. General treatment approaches, such as "Life Participation Approach" and "Computer-based treatments" were excluded. The remaining treatments were searched for by name in relevant bibliographic databases. Participant(s): No participants included. Intervention(s): 17 interventions were reviewed. Main Outcome Measure(s): Identification and assessment of true/versus/false replications studies within aphasia treatment methods. Result(s): Twelve out of seventeen treatments had been replicated by authors other than the original author. Two had not been replicated by authors outside the original author but had been replicated by the original authors in at least two additional publications. Conclusion(s): A lack of replication for these treatments puts their usability and generalizability at question. We encourage researchers to value replication by compiling and maintaining treatment manuals that can be shared with others. Researchers may find other ways to facilitate replication beyond their own research group. We recommend that replication studies be accepted for publication and be treated with the respect worth any study supporting evidence-based practice. Author(s) Disclosures: No relevant financial disclosures for S. Karidas. Relevant nonfinancial disclosures for S. Karidas: ANCDS Membership Committee Relevant financial disclosures for J. Hinckley: Project Lead for "Building a bigger BRIDGE", funded through a Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI) Eugene Washington PCORI Engagement Award (17449-NSU). Relevant nonfinancial disclosures for J. Hinckley: Advisory Board of the National Aphasia Association; Member, ACRM Special Interest Group on Stroke and Aphasia; Certification Board Member, Academy of Neurologic Communication Disorders & Sciences Keywords: Aphasia, Treatment, Replication, ASHA Practice Portal, Evidence-BasedCopyright © 2020
