162. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2008381976
T1  - Strategies for Engaging Patients with Communication Disabilities into Research and Services
T3  - American Congress of Rehabilitation Medicine 2020. Atlanta United States.
A1  - Hinckley J.
A1  - Demetropolis S.
A1  - Stillman F. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Research Objectives: Despite the accumulation of knowledge about how to engage the viewpoints of people who are affected by research and clinical efforts into the planning process (Bombard et al, 2018; Carman et al, 2014,Kirwan et al, 2017), people with communication disabilities or differences are often excluded from participation. Strategies for engaging patient perspectives into active research or service planning can be adapted for those with aphasia and related neurologic communication disabilities (Hinckley, Boyle, Lombard, & Bartels-Tobin, 2014). The purpose of this paper is to highlight evidence-supported engagement strategies for those with communication disabilities. Design(s): The project is based on principles of community-based participatory research. Setting(s): Multi-stakeholder teams and initiatives around the U.S. are supported through publicly available training efforts and the dissemination of evidence-supported practices. Participant(s): A total of 9 people with aphasia due to stroke, 8 care partners, 4 researchers and 3 clinicians participated collaboratively in 3 different settings to select a research topic, design a research question, or provide input on aspects of an experimental treatment. Intervention(s): Effective engagement strategies for people with aphasia and related communication disabilities included 1) appropriate preparation by providing pre-engagement training using aphasia-friendly principles, and 2) active engagement through the application of supported communication. Main Outcome Measure(s): Results of post-engagement surveys and interviews. Result(s): People with aphasia and their family members who participated in research question development reported a high degree of satisfaction with the engagement process. The result of the researchers and clinician's taking over the decision-making roles in the development of a research topic led to greater dissatisfaction with the process. The research topic selection, research question development, and research procedures were positively changed by the patient partner participation. Conclusion(s): When principles of preparation and engagement are melded with evidence-based techniques for aphasia-friendly communication, people with aphasia and their family members are able to participate in research and service planning. Author(s) Disclosures: This paper was partially funded through a Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI) Eugene Washington PCORI Engagement Award (17449-NSU), Jackie Hinckley, Project Lead. Keywords: Health Services Research, Patient Participation, Community-Based Participatory Research, Stroke, AphasiaCopyright © 2020
