A1  - Hinckley J. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Research Objectives: This study investigated whether and how age and aphasia affect performance of multi-tasking in a role-play scenario. Design(s): A between-groups design compared performances of younger and older adults without aphasia and adults with aphasia in single and concurrent task conditions. Setting(s): A catalog-ordering task (COT) was developed (Hinckley, Patterson, & Carr, 2001) to investigate multi-tasking during functional activity in individuals with aphasia. Real-catalog ordering scripts as an initial source were provided. The protocol was developed based on the most frequently occurring event sequences, grammatical forms, and vocabulary. In the single-task condition, participants completed catalog-ordering role play in quiet setting. In concurrent-task condition, a tone-detection task was added to investigate functional multi-tasking performance. Participant(s): 33 individuals with moderate to severe non-fluent aphasia. 25 college-age adults, 10 adults aged 44-74 years without aphasia served as controls. Intervention(s): N/A. Main Outcome Measure(s): Overall accuracy of task completion. Result(s): No differences in accuracy between performances of younger/older adults without aphasia in either task condition. Adults with aphasia had significantly poorer accuracy in both single/concurrent task conditions. The concurrent task further disrupted their ability to complete the task accurately. There was a moderately strong correlation between severity of aphasia and task accuracy in both the single-task and concurrent-task conditions. Conclusion(s): Although few tools exist that can be used for multi-tasking assessment, the COT is an example of a way in which a functional task can be measured in a single and multi-tasking context. More clinical attention should be paid to multi-tasking as an important aspect of functional abilities in aphasia. Author(s) Disclosures: No relevant financial disclosures for S. Karidas. Relevant nonfinancial disclosures for S. Karidas. ANCDS Membership Committee Relevant financial disclosures for J. Hinckley: * Project Lead for "Building a bigger BRIDGE", funded through a Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI) Eugene Washington PCORI Engagement Award (17449-NSU). Relevant nonfinancial disclosures for J. Hinckley: * Advisory Board of the National Aphasia Association * Member, ACRM Special Interest Group on Stroke and Aphasia * Certification Board Member, Academy of Neurologic Communication Disorders & Sciences Keywords: Aphasia, Multi-Tasking Assessment, Assessment, Functional AssessmentCopyright © 2020
