T1  - EXTRAHEPATIC MANIFESTATIONS OF NON-ALCOHOLIC FATTY LIVER DISEASE (NAFLD) POSE SIGNIFICANT CLINICAL AND ECONOMIC BURDEN ON THE MEDICARE POPULATION
T3  - Digestive Disease Week, DDW 2019. San Diego United States.
A1  - Sayiner M.
A1  - Golabi P.
A1  - Paik J.
A1  - Keo W.
A1  - Erario M.
A1  - Younossi Z.M. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background and Aim: NAFLD is associated with a number of extrahepatic manifestations (EHMs). The aim of the current study is to assess the impact of these EHMs on mortality and resource utilization of NAFLD patients with Medicare. Method(s): Medicare beneficiaries (2005-2016) were included. ICD-9 and ICD-10 codes were used to identify patients with NAFLD and EHMs which included cardiovascular disease (CVD), hypertension (HTN), diabetes (DM), hyperlipidemia (HL), any cancer except hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), lung disease, renal failure, thyroid disorder, depression, neurologic disorder, obstructive sleep apnea, osteoporosis, dementia, psoriasis and polycystic ovary syndrome. Temporal trends among different groups were analyzed by join point regression model. Independent predictors of outcomes were evaluated in multiple generalized linear or logistic regression models. All analyses were performed using SAS version 9.4 (SAS Institute Inc., Cary, NC). Result(s): Among 30,908,679 Medicare beneficiaries (5% sample of Medicare data from 2005-2016), 1,980,950 (6.4%) had NAFLD diagnosis (age 70.1 years, 45.4% male, and 78.7% non-Hispanic white). NAFLD prevalence rate per 1,000 Medicare population increased from 51.2 in 2005 to 70.3 in 2016, with an average annual increase of 3.1%. Comparing 2016 to 2005, rate of NAFLD-cirrhosis in Medicare population increased by 59% (from 2.22 to 3.54 per 1,000 population). Similarly, the rate of NAFLD-HCC doubled (from 0.09 to 0.18 per 1,000 population). Among patients with NAFLD, the most common EHMs were DM (86.3%), followed by HTN (85.2%), HL (79.8%), CVD (35.8%), lung disease (18.1%), renal failure (15.8%), thyroid disorder (15.0%), and depression (9.5%). One-year mortality rate for NAFLD increased from 3.55 per 1,000 in 2005 to 6.33 per 1,000 in 2016. One-year mortality was independently associated with HCC, cirrhosis, DM (outpatient), depression, CVD, dementia, lung disease, renal failure, thyroid disorder (inpatient), neurological disorder, and any cancer except HCC (Table). Total charge per patient in inpatients increased 83.5% from $46,254 to $84,867 as well as in outpatients increased 285% from $3,896 to $11,098. Conclusion(s): NAFLD is associated with a number of EHMs which are associated with mortality and increased resource utilization in the Medicare population. [Table presented]Copyright © 2019 AGA Institute. All rights reserved.
