169. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2001642720
T1  - A CASE FOR CAUTION: THE USE OF ESTROGEN CONTRACEPTION AND HYPERTRIGLYCEREDMIA
T3  - 68th Annual Scientific Session of the American College of Cardiology: ACC.19. New Orleans United States.
A1  - Kline K.
A1  - Evanchan J.
A1  - Harfi T. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background: Elevated triglyceride levels have an independent association with cardiovascular events and are becoming an increasingly recognized secondary target for hyperlipidemia. At least moderate hypertriglyceridemia (500-1000 mg/dL) is uncommon, in only 1.7% of the population. We present a case of presumed familial hypertriglyceridemia for several years duration being driven by combined oral contraception (COC). Case: A 34 year old woman with history of polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), obesity and presumed familial hypertriglyceridemia presented to our clinic after a several year history of serum triglycerides levels of 800-1000 mg/dl. Her medications included COC using norgestimate/ethinyl estradiol for symptom control of her PCOS. Given her metabolic profile and lab values it was concerning that the COC was grossly exacerbating her lipid profile. Decision-making: Oral based estrogen replacement formulations and higher strengths of ethinyl estradiol have shown greater effect on triglyceride levels. Those with a genetic predisposition to hypertriglyceridemia typically have only mild elevations in serum triglycerides, however marked elevations often occur when a secondary insult is present. Her COC was discontinued and she was started on low dose Rosuvastatin 10 mg and fenofibrate 160 mg daily. Her triglycerides improved dramatically at 4 month follow up from 966 to 141 mg/dl. This dual combination therapy would be expected to decrease serum triglycerides by 30-50%, whereas our patient had a striking 85% decrease suggesting significant contribution from her COC. Her fenofibrate was then discontinued and triglycerides remained improved at 4 month follow up to 218 mg/dl, supporting that the COC strongly influenced her lipid profile. Conclusion(s): While COCs are known to cause mild elevation in triglyceride level, they can be associated with severe hypertriglyceridemia in some patients. Recognizing such uncommon side effect of COC is important to avoid unnecessary testing, medical therapies and prevention of adverse sequelae such as pancreatitis and atherosclerosis.Copyright  2019 American College of Cardiology Foundation. All rights reserved.
