170. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2001641811
T1  - UTILITY OF CARDIAC MRI AND LATE GADOLINIUM ENHANCEMENT IN NEW ONSET BIVENTRICULAR HEART FAILURE: A CASE OF A YOUNG FEMALE WITH ACQUIRED HYPERCOAGULABLE STATE AND NORMAL CORONARY ARTERIES
T3  - 68th Annual Scientific Session of the American College of Cardiology: ACC.19. New Orleans United States.
A1  - Hill E.
A1  - Vanichsarn C.
A1  - Venkateswaran A.
A1  - Hu P.
A1  - Patel M.
A1  - Gonzalez J. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background: Cardiac MRI can provide key data about structure and function when ascertaining the etiology of heart failure. We present a case of a patient with new onset heart failure where cardiac MRI helped establish a diagnosis. Case: A 30-year-old obese female presented with progressive dyspnea on exertion. Her history included tobacco abuse and polycystic ovarian syndrome, managed with a combined hormonal vaginal contraceptive ring. Her remaining history was unremarkable. She presented with undifferentiated shock and hypoxemic respiratory failure. Troponin I was elevated but flat on repeat at 1.8 ng/mL (<0.03 ng/mL). Electrocardiogram revealed sinus rhythm and pathologic Q waves in leads V1-V4. Chest CT revealed pulmonary emboli and infarcts. Transthoracic echocardiogram revealed biventricular dilatation and dysfunction and apical akinesis with left ventricular thrombus. Decision-making: Right heart catheterization revealed cardiogenic shock, necessitating inotropic support. Top considerations for a cause of arterial and venous thromboembolism and biventricular heart failure included: 1) acquired or inherited hypercoagulable state with a shunt mechanism resulting in an embolic myocardial infarction and 2) primary myocardial condition, leading to decreased functional status and development of venous thromboembolism. Hypercoagulable testing was negative. Noninvasive ischemic evaluation with cardiac CT suggested a stress-induced cardiomyopathy. Given the discordant history and imaging, cardiac MRI was performed, showing transmural late gadolinium enhancement (LGE) of the anterior-apical walls, suggesting an ischemic etiology. Coronary angiogram validated the cardiac CT with normal coronary arteries. The patient was diagnosed with the clinical entity of a myocardial infarction with nonobstructive coronary arteries (MINOCA) contributing to left heart failure. Her right heart failure was secondary to pulmonary emboli due to an acquired hypercoagulable state. Conclusion(s): In cases of myocardial infarction yet no epicardial coronary artery disease, cardiac MRI can provide diagnostic evidence for MINOCA by delayed gadolinium imaging analysis.Copyright  2019 American College of Cardiology Foundation. All rights reserved.
