194. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 631884624
T1  - Vasoaugmentation therapy in acute ischemic stroke using milrinone, an initial series
T3  - 17th Annual Meeting, Neurocritical Care Society. Vancouver, BC Canada.
A1  - Hadhiah K.
A1  - Al-Jehani H.
A1  - Alabbas F.
A1  - Angle M.
A1  - Teitilbaum J. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Introduction Acute ischemic stroke is the second leading cause of death, especially if the patient did not receive the appropriate treatment geared towards a timely recanalization of the occluded vessels, including intravenous tissue plasminogen activator (IV t-PA) or endovascular thrombectomy. Little emphasis is given to the augmentation of collateral flow to offset the deleterious effect of ischemia or lessen the progression of the penumbral tissue into infarction. We present our initial experience with such vasoaugmentation strategy in patients with acute ischemic strokes. Methods We present our case series from King Fahad hospital of the university, Imam Abdulrahman bin Faisal University. Our series included 12 patients with acute ischemic strokes. We excluded patients with a large vessel occlusion. All other patients were included regardless of whether they received IV-tPA or not. All patients had a CT angiogram including collateral imaging and CT perfusion study at baseline. After explaining to the patients or their next-of-kin, we started the patients on a standardized protocol of milrinone (50mcg/kg bolus followed by 0.75mcg/kg/minute). Outcome assessment was comparing the initial mRS and that of the mRS at discharge. Chi square contingency analysis was used with a set level of significance of p < 0.05. Results Out of the 12 patients, 7 had good collaterals and 5 had poor collaterals. One of those poor collaterals patient had good cross flow from Pcom to the affected hemisphere, but still demonstrated poor collateral score. In our cohort, 8 (66%) achieved good neurological outcome of mRS of 4 or below with 3 patients (25%) achieving a discharge mRS of 0. Conclusions From this we conclude that the most important factor in initiation of milrinone is the presence of collaterals and small infarction core. The presence of cross flow wasn't helpful.
