196. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 630354671
T1  - Nivolumab-induced hypophysitis
T3  - 2019 International Conference of the American Thoracic Society , ATS 2019. Dallas, TX United States.
A1  - Reaven M.
A1  - Bender W.
A1  - Swenson C. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Nivolumab is an anti-programmed cell death protein 1 (PD-1) antibody used in the treatment of various types of cancer, including melanoma, renal cell carcinoma, and non-small cell lung cancer. A rare complication of nivolumab is hypophysitis, which has only been described in a few case reports across the world. Here we present a case of a man being treated with nivolumab for sarcomatoid lung cancer who developed hypophysitis and adrenal crisis. Case History: An 80 year old man was transferred to our intensive care unit (ICU) for hypercapnic respiratory failure and altered mental status. He had a history of stage 3B poorly differentiated sarcomatoid lung cancer on nivolumab, hypothyroidism, coronary artery disease, type 2 diabetes, and prostate cancer. On admission to the ICU he was in respiratory distress requiring intubation with an initial PCO2 of 70 mmHg. He was also profoundly hypotensive with mean arterial pressure of 38 mmHg requiring vasopressors. Laboratory evaluation revealed a total T4 level of 2.8 mcg/dL, total T3 level of 40 ng/dL, and TSH level of 83 mIU/L. A cosyntropin stimulation test done the day of transfer was normal. MRI of the pituitary revealed a thickened and prominent infundibulum consistent with hypophysitis. He was started on high dose steroids and intravenous T4 with rapid resolution of his symptoms. He was discharged from the hospital one week after ICU admission. Importance: Nivolumab induced hypophysitis is extremely rare, with only a few case reports existing in the literature. It can be a life threatening emergency causing rapid development of shock, respiratory failure, and altered mental status. Treatment consists of discontinuing the offending agent, administering high dose corticosteroids, as well as thyroid hormone replacement. It is critically important that intensivists be aware of this rare but serious complication as nivolumab becomes more widely used.
