199. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 629630064
T1  - Viral infection triggered malignant hyperthermia episode
T3  - 48th Critical Care Congress of the Society of Critical Care Medicine, SCCM 2019. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Hardy T.
A1  - Marvin W. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Learning Objectives: Malignant hyperthermia (MH) is a hypermetabolic crisis that is typically associated with exposure to a volatile anesthetic or succinylcholine in an MH susceptible person. There is likely a continuum between severe rhabdomyolysis and malignant hyperthermia in certain genetically predisposed people. Method(s): We report a 6-year-old African American female who developed severe rhabdomyolysis and a malignant hyperthermia episode with cardiac arrest triggered by a viral infection. Her past medical history was significant for adoption at 3 years of age from Ethiopia and subsequent gross motor delay that was presumed to be a result of the neglect she sustained prior to adoption. She presented to an outside hospital in cardiac arrest after 2 weeks of intermittent vomiting, progressive weakness resulting in the inability to ambulate, and significant hyperesthesias. She had return of spontaneous circulation after approximately 10 minutes total arrest time during which she was intubated with rocuronium alone and then was transferred to the PICU. Initial lactate was 10.7 mmol/L and CK was 40,000 U/L. pCO2 was not initially obtained but peak was noted to be 70 mmHg shortly after intubation. She had a profound persistent metabolic acidosis and tachycardia. She remained hyperthermic for 2 weeks and had extreme creatine kinase elevation that peaked at 200,143 U/L on hospital day 2. Her course was complicated by hypoxic ischemic brain injury, recurrent fevers with extensive infectious workup which resulted in positive PCR tests for parainfluenza and HSV1. She was eventually transferred to inpatient rehabilitation and currently is slowly regaining speech as well as fine and gross motor skills. She was found to have a ryanodine receptor (RYR1) gene mutation that is associated with increased susceptibility to rhabdomyolysis and malignant hyperthermia. Result(s): This was a unique case of a viral triggered MH crisis in a patient with an unknown RYR1 mutation. RYR1 mutations should be considered in patients with MH symptomatology (such as severe rhabdomyolysis) even when not exposed to a volatile anesthetic or succinylcholine especially in the setting of an intercurrent viral infection.
