200. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2002982987
T1  - CARDIOPULMONARY SYNDROMES: A HYPOXEMIC LINK BETWEEN COPD AND TAKOTSUBO CARDIOMYOPATHY
T3  - CHEST 2019 Annual Meeting. New Orleans United States.
A1  - Ali S.
A1  - Maknojia A.
A1  - hansen Z.
A1  - El-Oshar S. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - SESSION TITLE: Wednesday Medical Student/Resident Case Report Posters SESSION TYPE: Med Student/Res Case Rep Postr PRESENTED ON: 10/23/2019 09:45 AM - 10:45 AM INTRODUCTION: Takotsubo cardiomyopathy is a stress-induced left ventricular dysfunction believed to be caused by excess catecholamines in the absence of an alternative explanation. A retrospective analysis and a few case reports found an association between COPD and Takotsubo cardiomyopathy (1-3), but confounding variables during exacerbations make it difficult to determine direct causality. Consideration should be given for a separate entity, known as a cardiopulmonary syndrome, with changes in the lung leading to changes in the heart. CASE PRESENTATION: 66-year-old female with HTN, scleroderma, and COPD, presented with acute on chronic dyspnea with wheezing. She denied chest pain or weight gain. She only used albuterol PRN and denied frequent COPD exacerbations. She was in respiratory distress, tachypneic at 24 bpm, tachycardic at 125 bpm, using accessory muscles with marked diminished breath sounds. ABG revealed pH 7.31, pCO2 50, and paO2 188 on 50% venti mask, WBC 8.5, CO2 27, and lactic acid 3.2. CXR revealed no acute process. CTA was negative for PE. EKG revealed sinus tachycardia with new T-wave inversions in the inferolateral leads. She received 1mg of lorazepam for delirium tremens and decompensated. Repeat ABG revealed pH 6.92, pCO2 115, pO2 137, and she was emergently intubated. Repeat CXR showed no change. Mechanical ventilation improved ABG pCO2 to 36, However, she developed ventricular fibrillation with a troponin 0.487. Echo revealed EF of 15% (depressed from 50-55% last year), grade 2 diastolic dysfunction, an estimated PASP of 34mmhg, right ventricular dysfunction, apical akinesis and normal cardiac chamber dimensions. Catheterization showed 50% blockage of the LAD, normal circumflex and right coronary arteries with TIMI-3 flow. The patient began breath stacking and decompensated with atrial fibrillation and RVR, leading to withdrawal of care by her spouse. DISCUSSION: Takotsubo cardiomyopathy is due to ventricular dysfunction in response to physical or emotional stressors [4]. Proposed pathogenesis includes catecholamine excess leading to microvascular dysfunction, coronary vasospasm, and myocardial stunning [5, 6]. Stunned myocardium has been discussed in the setting of coronary ischemia and stable/unstable angina [7, 8]. The authors believe stunned cardiomyopathy may also exist from coronary hypoxemia due to COPD, proliferating cardiopulmonary decompensation, favoring recognition of a separate entity known as the cardiopulmonary syndromes. Type 1: acute respiratory illness causing acute heart failure Type 2: acute respiratory illness causing chronic heart failure Type 3: chronic respiratory illness causing acute heart failure Type 4: chronic respiratory illness causing chronic heart failure CONCLUSION(S): This classification of cardiopulmonary syndromes is meant to recognize and categorize coexisting pathology, and encourage guideline production for dual treatment modalities. Reference #1: Hertting K, Krause K, Harle T, Boczor S, Reimers J, Kuck KH. Transient left ventricular apical ballooning in a community hospital in Germany. Int J Cardiol. 2006;112:282-288. Reference #2: Pham J, Bruhl S, Sheikh M. COPD Exacerbation with Concurrent Stress Cardiomyopathy: A Case of Double Dyspnoea. BJMP 2011;4(1):a407 Reference #3: Landefeld K, Saleh Q, Sander GE. Stress Cardiomyopathy in the Setting of COPD Exacerbation. J Investig Med High Impact Case Rep. 2015;3(4):2324709615612847. Published 2015 Oct 14. DISCLOSURES: No relevant relationships by Shoheb Ali, source=Web Response No relevant relationships by Seraj El-Oshar, source=Web Response No relevant relationships by Zachary hansen, source=Web Response No relevant relationships by Arish Maknojia, source=Web ResponseCopyright © 2019 American College of Chest Physicians
