A1  - Papadopoulos M.C. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Introduction: Little is known about spinal cord blood flow (SCBF) in humans including the effect of changing blood pressure, changing arterial pCO2 or spinal cord injury (SCI). Here, we image SCBF in the dorsal columns intraoperatively using laser speckle contrast imaging (LSCI). Method(s): We recruited 4 patients without SCI (foramen magnum decompression, excision of spinal meningioma) and 22 patients with SCI. Inclusion criteria for SCI patients are: AIS A-C, 18-70 years old and surgery within 72h of injury. Surgery after SCI was fixation and laminectomies. In the SCI patients, we monitored spinal cord perfusion pressure and microdialysis from the injury site for 24h postoperatively. Mean patient follow-up after SCI was 7m. Result(s): We show that the LSCI signal is dampened by cerebrospinal fluid, but not dura. In patients without SCI we observed intact autoregulation, i.e. no change in SCBF with change in MAP, as well as SCBF variation with cardiac cycle, respiratory cycle and arterial pCO2. SCI patients had no cerebrospinal fluid around the injured cord because of cord oedema. We thus imaged SCBF with intact dura. Three pathological SCBF patterns were seen after SCI: Nonperfused cord with hypo-perfusion on either side, patchy SCBF and hyperaemia. We term these patterns necrosis-penumbra, patchyperfusion and hyper-perfusion, respectively. In general, increase in blood pressure (>20mmHg) increased overall injury site SCBF, but in 5/22 SCI patients SCBF increased in some regions but, surprisingly, decreased in other regions. We term this phenomenon blood pressure-induced local steal. In a group of SCI patients, regions within the injured cord were only perfused in systole, but not diastole. We term this phenomenon diastolic ischaemia. Low injury site SCBF correlated with low spinal cord perfusion pressure, low tissue glucose, high tissue lactate and less improvement in combined sensory AIS score (i.e. light touch + pin prick) at follow-up. Conclusion(s): LSCI can be used to visualise SCBF non-invasively with high spatial-temporal resolution. Using this technique, we discovered previously unrecognised pathological SCBF patterns after SCI and some unanticipated SCBF responses to blood pressure changes.
