232. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 623113180
T1  - Silver-russell syndrome in a woman with congenital adrenal hyperplasia due to reduced 3-beta-hsd expression, familial combined hyperlipidemia, and multiple other endocrine disorders associated with insulin resistance
T3  - 100th Annual Meeting of the Endocrine Society, ENDO 2018. Chicago, IL United States.
A1  - Jain V.
A1  - Ogrin C.
A1  - Guber H.A.
A1  - Sacerdote A. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - The number of disorders associated with insulin resistance (IR) has been growing exponentially and now includes PCOS, non-classic adrenal hyperplasia (NCAH), classic adrenal hyperplasia (CAH), differentiated thyroid carcinoma (DTC), mixed hyperlipidemia, and Silver-Russell syndrome (SRS). SRS is characterized by severe intrauterine and postnatal growth retardation with dimorphic facial features. Up to 65% of SRS patients have methylation defects in the H19 imprinted domain on chromosome 11 which codes for the IGF-2 receptor. The hypomethylation defect is associated with increased levels of Insulin like growth factor 1 which is indicative of reduced sensitivity to IGF- 1.Clinical case: A 43 year-old woman with oligomenorrhea and hirsutism, diagnosed with SRS during childhood, was referred to our clinic because of infertility. Diagnostic evaluation suggested nonclassical congenital adrenal hyperplasia due to reduced 3-beta-HSD expression. This patient had baseline 17-OH pregnenolone levels of 77 ng/dL(Normal range 20-450) and the levels were 2049 ng/dL( Normal range 290-910ng/dL) at 60 minutes after cosyntropin stimulation test. Later after treatment with dexamethasone the baseline 17-OH Pregnenolone was 50ng/dL. Following 2 1/2 months of dexamethasone 0.5mg f/b 0.25mg bid she began having monthly menses, and after 7 months she conceived. At the age of 26, She was diagnosed with cm minimally invasive follicular) s/p rt lobectomy followed by complete thyroidectomy. When patient was referred to us she was on Lipitor 40mg daily and her LDL was 188 with total cholesterol of 245, HDL 33 and TG 119. At 31 years of age she had chest pain and due to strong family history underwent angiogram which showed triple vessel disease and later underwent CABG. Conclusion(s): Several publications exist on the genetics and clinical presentation of SRS during childhood; however, there is a paucity of information for individuals beyond their mid-teens. This is the first reported case of a patient with SRS, reduced expression of 3-beta-HSD, and FH. She had concomitant presence of multiple endocrine disorders including FH associated with a strong propensity for premature coronary artery disease, thyroid carcinoma, hyperprolactinemia, Rathke's cleft cyst, diabetes, and osteopenia.A remarkably high proportion of these disorders are associated with IR. An additional potentially unifying mechanism is that methylation abnormalities associated with SRS also affect the expression of other genes; this second hypothesis being particularly attractive with regard to her 3-beta-HSD deficiency, since the more common non-classic form is not associated with any known exonic mutations. Our patient is the second oldest surviving person with SRS.We recommend that patients with SRS undergo evaluation for pituitary-adrenal-gonadal axis dysfunction and other metabolic dysfunction.
