233. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 623004445
T1  - Self-regulation in illness and treatment in post-stroke patients
T3  - 27th European Stroke Conference, ESC 2018. Athens Greece.
A1  - Kovyazina M.
A1  - Rasskazova E.
A1  - Aziatskaya G.
A1  - Prigorneva E.
A1  - Mokienko O.
A1  - Suponeva N.
A1  - Piradov M. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Question. Self-regulation in illness and treatment is a process of patient''s search for meaning in his situation (Leventhal et al., 2003). It is of extreme importance in neurorehabilitation process, where treatment efficacy depends on persistent personal engagement in treatment. The aim of the study was to assess self-regulation in rehabilitation in post-stroke patients with arm paresis. Methods. 27 hemiplegie patients after first-time stroke (age 51+/-14,8, time since stroke 7+/-5 months) were examined using MOCA, revised Illness Perception Questionnaire, Mindful Attention Awareness Scale, Goal Disengagement and Reengagement Scale, Satisfaction With Life Scale and Positive and Negative Feelings Scale, Rehabilitation Representation Questionnaire. Results. Self-efficacy in rehabilitation is higher in mindful patients who are capable to reengage in new goals and believe that they can control their illness (r=.40-.66). Subjective helplessness in rehabilitation is related to lower grit and less persistent achievement of goals as well as with lower mindfulness and readiness to change goals (r=-.52-.41). External locus of control of treatment is related to higher level of helplessness and anxiety (r=.45-.52). Self-efficacy in rehabilitation is a protective factor for negative emotions (r=-.43). Statistical adjusting for cognitive disturbance didn't change the pattern of results. Conclusions. In post-stroke patients feeling of self-efficacy and control in rehabilitation is related to better well-being regardless cognitive status. Treatment-related self-efficacy might be improved by better mindfulness, goal reengagement while treatment-related control-by intrinsic locus of control. Taking into account treatment-related self-regulation factors could help to individualize psychological rehabilitation.
