235. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622969722
T1  - Impact of co-morbid conditions on the outcome of patients admitted to the intensive care unit with exacerbation of COPD
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2018. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Saladi L.N.
A1  - Ravi P.
A1  - Venkatram S.
A1  - Diaz-Fuentes G. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Introduction: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is the third leading cause of mortality in the US and these patients are frequently admitted to the intensive care unit (ICU) with acute exacerbation of COPD (AECOPD). Few studies show that co-morbid conditions are related to morbidity and mortality in those patients. Our goal was to correlate the impact of co-morbidities and outcomes of patients with AECOPD admitted to ICU. Method(s): Retrospective analysis of patients with AECOPD admitted to the ICU between January 2014 and July 2016. Demographics, co-morbidities and laboratory parameters were analyzed. Primary outcome was effect of co-morbidities and select laboratory parameters on mortality. Result(s): 349 patients were admitted to ICU with AECOPD during the study period, the median age was 66 +/- 10 years and 218 (62%) were females. 72% of our patients had at least one co-morbid condition, the most common being hypertension. 29 (8.3%) patients died during hospitalization, we found no correlation between presence of co-morbid conditions and mortality. There was no difference in GOLD stage between survivors and non-survivors. Presence of pneumonia was associated with increased ICU and hospital LOS. LOS on MV was greater for patients with increase in number of co-morbidities, presence of coronary artery disease or gastroesophageal reflux (GERD). Stepwise multivariate logistic regression analysis revealed that high creatinine was associated with increased mortality (OR=0.67 C 95% 0.50 to 0.90; p=0.005). APACHE 4 score, pCO2 and serum albumin levels were associated with increased need for mechanical ventilation (OR=1.05 C 95% 1.03 to 1.08; p<0.001, OR=1.02 C 95% 1.00 to 1.04; p=0.023 and OR=0.38 C 95% 0.21 to 0.69; p=0.001 respectively); same parameters increased hospital LOS (OR=0.06 C 95% 0.00 to 0.13; p=0.045, OR=0.08 C 95% 0.03 to 0.15; p=0.003 and OR= -2.61 C 95% -4.56 to -0.67; p=0.008 respectively). Conclusion(s): Contrary to other studies, our data shows that presence and number of co-morbidities have no effect on mortality, need for MV or ICU/hospital LOS. Number of co-morbidities, presence of CAD and GERD increase LOS on MV. Serum creatinine on admission predicted mortality. Our inner-city population with COPD has increased number of comorbidities and there were more females admitted with AECOPD compared with other studies. Clinical Implications: Increased creatinine is associated with high mortality in patients with AECOPD likely due to cigarette smoke induced renal and pulmonary endothelial cell injury. Pneumonia on presentation increases morbidity. Aggressive management of CAD and GERD could have an impact in AECOPD. (Table presented) .
