236. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622966107
T1  - An unusual case of gastrointestinal-induced lung compression with hypoxia
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2018. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Delasos L.
A1  - Manek G.
A1  - Troy P. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Hiatal hernias are divided into two distinct groups: sliding and paraesophageal hernias. Among the different types of paraesophageal hernias, those associated with a large defect in the phrenoesophageal membrane and the presence of organs other than the stomach in the hernia sac (i.e. type IV) are a very uncommon finding. The presence of respiratory compromise from a giant hiatal hernia is even less common. Here we present a case of giant hiatal hernia associated with acute hypoxic respiratory failure. An 81-year-old male with history of coronary artery disease status-post triple bypass surgery, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and bilateral inguinal hernia repair presented to his PCP after experiencing a mechanical fall at home striking the left side of his chest against the arm of his chair. He complained only of pain along the left side of his chest, denying loss of consciousness, head trauma, or dyspnea. He was sent to the ED and found to be hypoxic to 90% on room air. The patient was placed on 2 L/min oxygen via nasal cannula with improvement in his oxygen saturation to 96%. CT scan of the chest revealed acute fractures of the left sixth, seventh, and eighth ribs as well as a very large hiatal hernia containing the entire stomach and a large segment of the transverse colon. Throughout his hospital stay, he continued to have falls in oxygen saturations below 90% when placed on room air and while sleeping. Nocturnal oximetry testing revealed a minimum SpO2 reading of 74% with 102 minutes recorded for SpO2 values less than 88%. Arterial blood gases showed chronic respiratory acidosis with elevated pCO2 and bicarbonate. Based on these findings, the cause of his acute hypoxic respiratory failure and respiratory acidosis was largely attributed to splinting from atelectasis complicated by his profound hiatal hernia which prevented full expansion of the lungs. In addition, his nocturnal hypoventilation was found to be a function of the large hiatal hernia itself. In summary, it has been estimated that paraesophageal hernias account for approximately 5% of hiatal hernias, with type IV making up only 5-10% of that population. Many of these patients are either asymptomatic or present with epigastric pain, postprandial fullness, nausea, and retching. Most complications are mechanical, with respiratory compromise being uncommon. This case illustrates a rare complication of large hiatal hernias, in which a patient's oxygenation requirements were increased due to the compressive nature of the hernia itself.
