238. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622327064
T1  - Acute ST elevation myocardial infarction with total occluded left main stem and cardiogenic shock-PCI or emergency CABG?
T3  - 23rd Cardiovascular Summit, TCTAP 2018. Seoul South Korea.
A1  - Voon C.Y.
A1  - Fong A.
A1  - Ong T.K. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - CLINICAL INFORMATION Patient Initials or Identifier Number. DJ Relevant Clinical History and Physical Exam. Mr. DJ, 57-year-old, active smoker. No other medical illness. At 22:40, he presented to other hospital for chest pain for past 3 hours. At ED, BP 66/52, bibasal lungs crepitation, SPO2 92% on high flow mask. ECG showed ST elevation at lead I, aVL, V2-6 with ST depression at inferior leads. He was intubated and supported with inotropes. ABG showed severe metabolic acidosis. Diagnosis: Anterior STEMI Khilip 4 with cardiogenic shock. He was transferred to our center for primary PCI. Relevant Test Results Prior to Catheterization. Renal profile: urea 4 mmol/ l, creatinine 135 umol/l. ABG (ventilated): pH 7.24, pCO2 36.3 mmHg, pO2 64 mmHg, HCO3 15.6 mmol/l, BE -11.4 mmol/l, SPO2 88.4%. CXR: acute pulmonary edema ECG: generalized ST elevation Echocardiography: severe LV global hypokinesia with EF < 25%, dilated IVC with elevated RV systolic pressure. Relevant Catheterization Findings. The initial coronary angiogram showed: LMS - total occluded distally with TIMI 0 flow at LAD and LCX RCA - normal INTERVENTIONAL MANAGEMENT Procedural Step. A 6Fr EBU 3.5 guiding catheter was used to engage LMS. PT2MS GW was used to cross the lesion into LCX. Aspiration catheter was used for multiple thrombus aspirations. GW re-crossed into LAD followed by multiple thrombus aspirations. A 1.5 x 12 mm and 2.5 x 15 mm SC balloons were used for POBA to distal LMS and ostial LAD. The final result showed TIMI 2 flow at LAD and TIMI 3 flow at LCX. IABP was inserted and IV Glycoprotein IIb/IIIa inhibitor infusion was commenced at 25 mcg/kg. His BP and heart rate remained stable without inotropic support after POBA to LMS-LAD and LMS-LCX. He was referred to a surgeon for emergency CABG. However, his condition deteriorated 12 hours after initial PCI which required triple inotropic support, eGFR 23 ml/min/1.73 m2. After urgent team discussion among cardiologists and cardiothoracic surgeons, rescue PCI was decided without further delay. After LMS engagement with a 6Fr EBU3.5 guiding catheter, two soft GWs were advanced into distal LAD and LCX, followed by POBA to LMS-LAD with 3.0 x 15 mm NC balloon. The LMS-LAD lesion was stented with a 3.5 x 18 mm DES. The GW was re-crossed into LCX. Final kissing was done using 3.75x10 mm and 2.0x10 mm NC balloon. The final result showed TIMI 3 flow in both LAD and LCX. Unfortunately, his condition remained critically ill and required prolonged intubation and ventilation. On Day 14 post-PCI, he succumbed due to severe sepsis. Conclusions. The initial aim of PCI to establish TIMI flow in LAD and LCX was achieved with POBA. Although his condition improved temporarily with stable BP and heart rate without inotropic support after POBA. However, complete revascularization was delayed, which eventually led to the irreversible myocardial injury. Therefore, sluggish myocardial recovery with severely impaired myocardial function leading to multi-organ failure, together with prolonged intubation and ventilation; which inevitably contributed to the morbidity and mortality. (Figure Presented).
