239. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622326797
T1  - Successful PCI for CTO via the previous implanted STENT strut in CPA patient treated with hemodialysis
T3  - 23rd Cardiovascular Summit, TCTAP 2018. Seoul South Korea.
A1  - Igarashi N. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - CLINICAL INFORMATION Patient Initials or Identifier Number. H.T Relevant Clinical History and Physical Exam. A-80-year-old man who led to CPA (Cardiopulmonary arrest) was taken in the ambulance to our hospital. We induced ECPR (Extracorporeal Cardio Pulmonary Resuscitation) for him. The down time was 60 minutes. Eight days later he could be detached from the mechanical support and became neurologically full recover. More five days later he led to CPA with VF again. Relevant Test Results Prior to Catheterization. WBC 8300/ml Hb 8.0 g/dl Ht 25.4% Plt 7200/ml Alb 2.3 AST 70IU/l ALT 40 IU/l LDH 262 IU/l BUN 40.8 mg/dl Cr 6.17mg/dl eGFR 6.3 ml/min 1.73m2 Na 135 mEq/l K 5.3 mEq/l Cl 100 mEq/l pH 7.26 PCO2 PO2 469 HCO3 17.3 BE-9.4 mmol/l AnGap 20.7 mmol/l Lactate 9.63 mmol/l ECG showed VF (Ventricula Fibrillation). Chest X ray showed Pulmonary edema. Relevant Catheterization Findings. An emergent coronary angiography showedmid LAD CTO that was covered with previous implanted stent across to the diagonal branch. Because of the recurrence of VF, we put a priority on the Targeted Temperature Management and the implantation of ICD. After that, we performed PCI for LAD CTO. INTERVENTIONAL MANAGEMENT Procedural Step. The previous implanted stent interfered with the antegrade guidewire crossing. Under anchor balloon technique, we couldn't advance retrograde Corsair Pro to the distal part of CTO lesion at the bifurcation of diagonal branch. However, we could advance the retrograde guidewire to the distal CTO lesion. We could advance the antegrade guidewire via the previous stent strut close to the retrograde guidewire. The retrograde guidewire was successfully passed through CTO lesion into the antegrade guiding catheter by reverse CART. Finally, we put the EES at mid LAD through the previous stent strut like a Y stenting. After that we saw the coronary perforation distal part of LAD. We performed to stop the bleeding with perfusion balloon. We could control the late cardiac tamponade only with pericardial drainage and didn't confirm the recurrence of VF. Conclusions. We successfully performed PCI for CTO that was covered with previous implanted stent across to the diagonal branch by Reverse CART. After stenting, we saw the coronary perforation at the distal part of LAD. We performed to stop the bleeding with perfusion balloon. We could control the late cardiac tamponade only with pericardial drainage. We rescued the CPA patient that had LAD CTO. (Figure Presented).
