240. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 622060816
T1  - Relationship between pattern of activated pathways and quality of collateral status in patients with internal carotid artery occlusion
T3  - 23rd Meeting of the European Society of Neurosonology and Cerebral Hemodynamics, ESNCH 2018. Prague Czechia.
A1  - Connolly F.
A1  - Rohl J.E.
A1  - Lopez-Prieto J.
A1  - Danyel L.
A1  - Schreiber S.
A1  - Valdueza J. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Background: Cerebral hemodynamics in patients with internal carotid artery (ICA) occlusion depends on the anatomy of the circle of Willis and the individual capacity to activate alternative pathways. The aim of this study was to compare the different pattern of activated pathways with the quality of collateral status in patients with unilateral ICA-occlusion (ICAO) using TCCS. Material(s) and Method(s): 64 patients were enrolled. Exclusion criteria: stenosis of the ipsilateral external carotid artery, the contralateral ICA or any intracranial artery >50%. The following collaterals were assessed: Anterior and posterior communicating artery (ACoA, PCoA), ophthalmic artery (OA) and lep-tomeningeal of the PCA (LMC). Quality of collateral status was assessed by analyzing the flow pattern in the MCA: (i) no or mild (good), (ii) moderate and (iii) severe or pseudovenous (bad) blunted flow. Result(s): 34/23/7 patients showed a good/moderate/bad collateral status. The following quantity of activated collaterals was found: ACoA: 53, OA: 44, PCoA: 31 and LMC: 19. Eleven/27/22/4 patients showed 1, 2, 3 and 4 activated pathways, respectively. Thirty-three (97%) patients with good collateral function had a cross-flow via the ACoA. LMC were mainly activated in patients with moderate or bad collateral status (good: 18%, moderate: 39%, bad: 57%). Anterograde OA was found in 14 patients (22%) and was associated with an activated PCoA in 11 cases (79%), whereas in patients with retrograde OA a PCoA collateral was observed in 43% (n = 19). Anterograde OA indicated a good collateral status (93%), whereas a retrograde OA was found in 21 (48%) and 5 (11%) patients with moderate and bad collateral status, respectively. Conclusion(s): The majority of patients with ICAO showed a good collateral status. Anterograde OA indicates hemodynamic stability and is associated with PCoA activation. A good collateral status is strongly associated with a cross-flow via the AcoA but not with the quantity of activated collaterals.
