258. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 621234400
T1  - Metabolic phenotype in cardiogenic shock due to acute myocardial infarction and end-stage heart failure
T3  - European Society of Cardiology, ESC Congress 2017. Barcelona Spain.
A1  - Lim H.S. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Background: Acute myocardial infarction (AMI) and end-stage heart failure (ESHF) are major causes of cardiogenic shock (CS). The chronicity and associated medical therapy may be expected to alter the 'metabolic phenotype' of CS due to ESHF, which may be relevant to the assessment of these patients. Purpose(s): To assess the metabolic profile in CS due to ESHF compared to AMI. Method(s): Single-centre study of consecutive patients with CS due to AMI or ESHF. CS was defined as cardiac index <2.2L/min/m2, systolic BP<90mmHg and evidence of hypoperfusion requiring inotropes. ESHF was defined as pre-existing HF >1 month duration. Pulmonary artery catheter was inserted routinely in all patients to measure mixed venous PCO2 and oxygen content. Base deficit (BD) was evaluated by the method described by Gilfix. The degree of anaerobic metabolism was measured by the ratio of the mixed venous (pulmonary artery)-arterial difference in partial pressure of CO2 to arterial-mixed venous difference in O2 content (dPCO2/dO2cont). Result(s): 45 patients (22 AMI, 23 ESHF) were included (Age: 44+/-5 vs 43+/-7 years, males: 68% vs 48%, cardiac arrest: 27% vs 13%, IABP: 68% vs 44%, inotrope score: 26+/-3 vs 24+/-2, mean BP: 58+/-3 vs 56+/-3mmHg, all P=NS). Patients with AMI had higher C-reactive protein (CRP): 166+/-32 vs 45+/-16, and base deficit (BD): - 8.9+/-0.8 vs -4.1+/-0.9 (p<0.001), which was largely related to unmeasured anions (XA), while lower chloride and albumin in ESHF reduced the overall BD [Figure, top]. Patients with AMI had higher arterial (18.2+/-0.4 vs 14.6+/-0.7ml) and venous (7.9+/-0.6 vs 5.3+/-0.5ml) oxygen content (both p<0.01). Arterial PCO2 were: 34+/-2 vs 36+/-2mmHg, p=NS and venous PCO2 were: 50+/-2 vs 52+/-2mmHg, p=0.046, respectively. The resultant dPCO2/dO2cont ratio was lower in AMI compared to ESHF (1.17+/-0.11 vs 1.36+/-0.10, p-0.002), suggesting less anaerobic metabolism. Despite lower dPCO2/dO2cont, lactate was higher in AMI patients: 7.2+/-0.6 vs 5.9+/-0.3 (p<0.001) [Figure, bottom], which also correlated with CRP levels in patients with AMI (r=0.762, p<0.001). Conclusion(s): CS due to AMI and ESHF have different metabolic phenotype, characterised by higher BD due to XA, and higher lactatemia, which appeared to be related inflammatory response in addition to anaerobic metabolism. Patients with CS due to ESHF had greater anaerobic metabolism but lower lactate (with less inflammatory response) and BD, as the latter was compensated by lower albumin and chloride. (Figure Presented).
