267. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 617705792
T1  - Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation in patients with acute severe asthma
T3  - American Thoracic Society International Conference, ATS 2017. Washington, DC United States.
A1  - Magge A.
A1  - Pascanu R.
A1  - Salerno E. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - Acute severe asthma poses a significant health and economic burden in the United States. Approximately 30 percent of all intensive care unit (ICU) admissions for asthma require intubation and mechanical ventilation with a mortality rate approximately 8 percent. Since the advent of extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO), there have been few documented case reports of its use in treatment of refractory asthma when there is severe dynamic hyperinflation or life-threatening respiratory acidosis despite medical and ventilator optimization. We describe a case where early ECMO evaluation and implementation significantly improved the patient's respiratory outcome. A 54 year old female with mild persistent asthma and an active smoker, presented to the emergency department with shortness of breath that started 8 hours prior. The patient complained of a dry cough for 3 days without fever, chills, or rhinorrhea but then later developed shortness of breath, which progressed to chest tightness with significant wheezing. Upon arrival to the ICU, the patient remained tachypneic and immediately intubated. Arterial blood gas (ABG) on admission revealed pH 7.14, pCO2 70, pO2 73, and HCO3 24. The patient had a worsening acidosis and due to significant peak inspiratory pressures, the patient was paralyzed. Due to overall deterioration and difficulty ventilating, the patient was placed on veno-venous ECMO 4 days after intubation. ABG showed significant improvement: pH 7.31, pCO2 47, HCO3 24, and pO2 84. The patient was weaned off ECMO after 5 days. Complications included pneumonia, tracheostomy and percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy tube placement, acute renal failure requiring hemodialysis, and bilateral thalamic strokes rendering the patient tracheostomy dependent and neurologically impaired. In the case above, early implementation of ECMO improved morbidity and mortality when mechanical ventilation and pharmacotherapy was not enough. This is also supported by the Conventional ventilatory support vs extracorporeal membrane oxygenation for severe adult respiratory failure (CESAR) trial, which was a multi-center effort that revealed a survival benefit with ECMO when compared to ventilation. Additionally, in a retrospective cohort study using the extracorporeal life support organization registry it was found that 93 percent of patients with status asthmaticus who received ECMO survived hospital discharge. Unfortunately, to this date no guidelines have been developed as to when to use ECMO in refractory asthma. Although, in most case reports, ECMO was initiated when patients reached life-threatening acidosis, it may be beneficial to assess the patient for ECMO earlier since this can lead to better outcomes.
