273. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 616813829
T1  - Hearing loss in osteogenesis imperfecta: Altered intracortical porosity and structure in the oim mice cochlea
T3  - 2017 Annual Meeting of the Orthopaedic Research Society. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Miller B.J.
A1  - Bodey A.
A1  - Doube M.
A1  - Carriero A. 
Y1  - 2017//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Osteogenesis imperfecta (OI or brittle bone disease) is a heritable bone disease caused by mutations of the collagen, the primary matrix protein in bone. OI results in extreme skeletal fragility, bone deformities, and spontaneous fracture. Approximately 50% of patients with OI experience significant hearing loss while an even greater percentage experience more mild auditory impairment [1]. However, to date, little is known about the ultrastructure and properties of the cochlear bone in OI subjects with hearing loss. The oim mouse model of OI mimics moderate to severe OI in humans. oim mice have brittle bones, with a less stiff collagen fibril and bone tissue matrix, and disorganized lamellar structure [2-4]. Our recent 3D synchrotron reconstruction of oim cortical bone showed similar porosity with C57BL6 WT bone, but increased number of smaller and branched canals populate these bones, and osteocyte lacunae are more dense and rounded in shape [2]. This altered intracortical architecture plays a fundamental role in the bone fracture origination and propagation, decreasing the overall bone toughness [2,3]. Although oim mice are widely used to investigate OI bone disease, unknown are the morphology and mechanical properties of their cochlea, the main hearing bone. To better understand hear-impairment in OI, we used synchrotron radiation-based computed tomography (SR CT) to characterize the ultrastructure of the cochlear bone in oim mice. METHOD(S): The inner ear bone compartment of six WT mice (C57BL/6) and six oim (B6C3Fe a/a-Col1a2oim/oim) mice, all 8 weeks-old and male, were dissected following euthanization, aligned and embedded at one end in bone cement (PMMA). During preparation and before imaging, the bones were wrapped in gauze with physiological solution, and then stored at -20degreeC. During scanning in the I13-2 beamline of Diamond Light Source in UK, bones were oriented with their longitudinal axis parallel to the stage rotation axis and high-resolution 3D grayscale images of the cochlea for both mouse strains were obtained using SR CT scans at a nominal resolution of 810 nm using a pco.edge 5.5 camera (2560 x 2160 pixels, field of view 2.1 x 1.8 mm) coupled to a CdWO4 scintillator and visual light microscope. A total of 3001 projections were collected uniformly over 180degree using a filtered polychromatic 'pink' beam of 5- 35keV with mean energy of 15 keV (30ms exposure per projection). Tomograms were reconstructed using filtered back-projection yielding images volumes consisting in 2159 images. Thresholding (histogram-based global algorithm in ImageJ) was used to segment the bone matrix from air and soft tissue (ref my Bone paper). Cortical bone, canals and osteocyte lacunae were segmented by using the 'Analyse Particle' routine in BoneJ. Furthermore, individual intracortical canals from branched networks were analyzed using the 'Skeletonize 3D'and the 'Analyze Skeleton' functions in BoneJ. At the tissue level, we analyzed cortical bone volume (Ct.TV), cortical bone porosity (Po.V/Ct.TV), canal number (N.Ca), canal number density (N.Ca/Ct.TV), canal volume density (Ca.V/Ct.TV), canal connectivity density (Ca.Conn.D), mean canal volume (), mean canal diameter (), mean canal length (). At the cellular level, number of osteocyte lacunae (N.Lc), lacuna number density (N.Lc/Ct.TV), lacuna volume density (Lc.V/Ct.TV), mean lacuna volume (), mean lacuna equancy, elongation and flatness (, , , respectively) and mean lacuna orientation () were examined. Statistical differences between the oim and WT bone properties having the same number of samples within the two groups were evaluated by performing the Student's independent t-test for the variables that had normal distributions while the Mann-Whitney rank test was used to evaluate variables with non-normal distributions. Mean properties of canal and lacunae deriving from different sample numbers were evaluated with multilevel linear models, which accounted for the hierarchical dependence of the sample from the specific bone within each group. Variables with p-values less than 0.05 were considered to be statistical significant. RESULT(S): Morphometric evaluation (Table 1) of the cortical bone porosity in WT and oim bone indicated a statistical significant increase in the porosity of the oim cortical bone (p-value < 0.05), with a statistical significant increase in the number and volume of canal density (p-value < 0.05), characterized by a higher canal connectivity density (p-value < 0.05). Differences in the mean canal volume, diameter and length, as well as morphological differences at the cellular level were not statistical significant between oim and WT bone. DISCUSSION: We collected and analyzed SR CT data that indicate greater bone porosity in oim cochleae than in WT. We believe that the greater number of highly branches canals may be responsible for the increased deafness in the oim mice. Previous studies have shown that fracture rate increases in bone with many, branched canals: cracks inititate at canal junction due to high local stress/strain concentration [2] and quickly propagate within the bone with high porosity [3], thus decreasing its toughness [5]. This increase in bone fractures may generate consequent deformities in the cochlea, adversely affecting its ability to detect sounds. Because fracture in brittle bone occurs with little load and under small overall tissue strain, high rates of fracture are common in OI patients. Understanding how these fractures generate and propagate in brittle bone and how this process affects the auditory system in OI can inform treatments to strengthen the cochlea bone in order to avoid deafness in patients with OI. Our sample size was limited: a larger samples size would allow us to investigate these differences in the oim bone in more detail; however, we have detected significant changes in porosity in oim cochlea bone. Overall cortical porosity was significantly different in the cochlear bone but not in our previous study examining long oim bone. This difference can be related to the number and type of bones analyzed, and/or to the WT bone used for comparison: in our previous study on long bone we used the standard C57BL6 mouse as WT, here we used the more appropriate control B6C3Fe-a/a-+/+. In both studies we found increased canal porosity with small statistical significance found for the canal mean morphometric indices. This is due to the high variance in the dataset. In long oim bone we found more rounded lacunae compared to WT. In the cochlea, lacunae have similar geometry between oim and WT and are more spherical and flat, and less elongated than in long bone, with a different orientation angle. This is in agreement with the mechanical environment imposed on these bones: cochela are subjected to a hydrostatic pressure as opposed to axial loading on long bones. In conclusion, we have demonstrated how canal networks and osteocyte lacunae contribute to 3D cortical porosity in oim cochlear bone. This may have implications in the mechanical integrity of the bone, thus affecting hearing capabilities. These findings might help to better understand deafness in human with OI.
